  "prompt": "Can educational testing services (ETS) sponsor cap-exempt H-1B visa?",
  "response": "Yes, Educational Testing Service (ETS) can sponsor a cap-exempt H-1B visa under certain conditions. \n\nThe H-1B visa program has an annual cap, but certain employers are exempt from this cap. These cap-exempt employers include:\n\n1. **Institutions of higher education** (colleges and universities) or related or affiliated nonprofit entities.\n2. **Nonprofit research organizations** or governmental research organizations.\n\nETS, as a nonprofit organization that is primarily engaged in educational testing and research, may qualify for cap-exempt status if it can demonstrate that it is affiliated with an institution of higher education or that it primarily engages in research and development in the field of education.\n\nTo sponsor a cap-exempt H-1B visa, ETS would need to:\n\n1. **Determine Eligibility**: Confirm that it qualifies as a cap-exempt employer under the criteria outlined above.\n2. **File the H-1B Petition**: Submit Form I-129, Petition for a Nonimmigrant Worker, to U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) along with supporting documentation.\n3. **Provide Evidence**: Include evidence of the cap-exempt status, such as documentation showing affiliation with an institution of higher education or proof of engagement in research activities.\n\nIf ETS meets the criteria, it can sponsor H-1B workers without being subject to the annual cap, allowing for year-round filing and processing of H-1B petitions.\n\nIt's always a good idea to consult with an experienced immigration attorney to ensure that all requirements are met and the process is handled correctly.",
